    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>First, you can switch on an <code>enum</code> in Java. I'm guessing you intended to say you can’t, but you can. <code>char</code>s have a set range of values, so it's easy to compare. Strings can be anything.</p>\n\n<p>A <code>switch</code> statement is usually implemented as a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Branch_table\" rel=\"nofollow\">jump table (branch table)</a> in the underlying compilation, which is only possible with a finite set of values. C# <em>can</em> switch on strings, but it causes a performance decrease because a jump table cannot be used.</p>\n\n<p>Java 7 and later supports <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/language/strings-switch.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>String</code> switches</a> with the same characteristics.</p>\n"
  }, {
